        <body>
           <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW">
            <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up"/>QENỊLOCI MAQI MAQI-AINIA MUC̣[OI]
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <p/>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>of Cellach son of Mac-Áine? descendant of?</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>QENN- (OIr <ref target="https://dil.ie/8622"><foreign xml:lang="ga">cenn</foreign></ref> `head'): ... QENILOCI (Cellach) (McManus 1991, 103).</p>
                <p>It is tempting to equate the name MAQI-AINIA with the goddess Áine but, as McManus (1991, 109, 115, 179 n. 47) points out, <q>if so AI must be an error for A as the first syllable does not contain the diphthong ai</q> and palatalisation is not written in ogham.</p>
                <p>The retention of the -I in QENILOCI in combination with the loss of -S in MAQI-AINIA suggests dating this inscription to the first half of the sixth century (McManus 1991, 95, 97).</p>
            </div>
